==English==
===Etymology===
Classical Greek: [[ιχωρ|ιχώρ]]
===Noun===
# the [[liquid]] that was in Greek Mythology said to flow in place of [[blood]] in the [[veins]] of the gods
# a watery discharge from a sore
====Quotations====
* '''1720''': This said, she wiped from Venus’ wounded palm / The sacred '''ichor''', and infused the balm. &mdash; Alexander Pope, ''The Iliad''
* '''1936''': Wrap him for shroud in a petal. / Embalm him with '''ichor''' of nettle. &mdash; Robert Frost, 'Departmental', 1936
* '''1989''': They will not live / As shades but angle forward to enjoy / The pluck of life, the pressure of their '''ichor'''. &mdash; Peter Porter, 'They Come Back More', from ''Possible Worlds'', 1989

